  "facts": [
    "The expression comes from the French noun \"coulisse\"—originally the sliding side-panels or wings of a theater stage—so \"en coulisses\" literally meant \"in the wings,\" and French preserves the plural even when referring to a single backstage sphere.",
    "Outside the theater, \"en coulisses\" is a journalistic and diplomatic staple for negotiations or influence conducted informally or privately, and English often borrows the phrase unchanged to add a slightly clandestine, theatrical nuance.",
    "Across languages many cultures use theatrical metaphors for secrecy—German \"hinter den Kulissen\" (Kulissen is a cognate), Spanish \"entre bambalinas,\" etc.—because the stage has long been a natural metaphor for power, performance and behind-the-scenes maneuvering."
  ]
